Staying healthy is an important part of education. If your child doesn’t have health insurance, you may qualify for KCHIP, Kentucky Children’s Health Insurance Program. It provides comprehensive coverage at no cost.

Enroll your kids up to age 19 in no-cost health care coverage through the Commonwealth of Kentucky. Signing up is simple, coverage is complete, and it’s the right thing to do.

Apply online at kidshealth.ky.gov or call toll free 1-877-KCHIP-18 (1-877-524-4718).
An informational video can be viewed @ https://bit.ly/3bOAtnV #murrayschools

post_text:
MISD Reopening Update - In Person Instruction at Murray High School

In order to provide quality instruction for all students at Murray High, students that select In Person Instruction will attend 4 days per week (Monday, Tuesday, Thursday & Friday) and participate in Online Learning 1 day per week (Wednesday). Students who have chosen Online Learning, will participate all 5 days virtually.
At this time, this schedule will remain in place through the end of the first quarter of instruction, Friday, October 16th. We will revisit the schedule as needed at that time and communicate with all stakeholders before we begin the second grading period on October 19th.
Murray High ninth graders will begin on Monday, September 14th. MHS 10th-12th graders will begin on Tuesday, September 15th. Wednesday, September 16th will be an Online Learning day for all Murray High students.
Murray High School staff will be contacting your families this week to confirm your instructional choice. #murrayschools

post_text:
Murray Independent School District Athletics Announces Live Streaming Events for Football, Volleyball and Basketball

Ann Greenfield, Murray Independent School District Athletic Director, said plans are in place to begin live-streaming of all home Middle and High school football, volleyball, and basketball games. Games will be streamed live by The National Federation of high school sports through the MISD Athletic website.

To access games, a $10.99 cost per month, or $69.99 for an all-season fee is applicable. Access to this link is posted on the MISD Athletic website https://bit.ly/3jIXlbl. Click on the NFHS Murray High “Live Stream” link to subscribe.

Greenfield said it is important to provide different viewing options for these games to our fan base near and far.

Please note- (No General Admission Tickets will be sold for the home girls soccer match versus McCracken County, Thursday, September 10.)

The Murray Independent School District (MISD) Board of Education conducted a special called board meeting on Thursday, Sept. 3, 2020, to review the MISD 2020-2021 Re-Opening Plan. After thorough consideration of COVID-19 data for Murray and Calloway County, the board voted to begin offering a blended approach of on-line and in-person instruction for students to begin at the Superintendent's discretion no earlier than Sept. 10, 2020.

Coy Samons, MISD superintendent, school principals, and central office personnel will be providing more details in the upcoming days.

The Murray Independent School District (MISD) Board of Education conducted a special called board meeting on Thursday, Sept. 3, 2020, to review the MISD 2020-2021 Re-Opening Plan. After thorough consideration of COVID-19 data for Murray and Calloway County, the board voted to begin offering a blended approach of on-line and in-person instruction for students to begin at the Superintendent's discretion no earlier than Sept. 10, 2020.

Coy Samons, MISD superintendent, school principals, and central office personnel will be providing more details in the upcoming days.

post_text:
MISD families and stakeholders:

Updated full details regarding Online Learning, Devices & Internet access, and meal pickup options are available on the MISD Returning to School site: https://murray.kyschools.us/misd2021

If you have any questions please contact your child’s respective school, as they will be able to answer your questions or direct your call: Murray Elementary School (270) 753-5022, Murray Middle School (270) 753-5125, and Murray High School (270) 753-5202,

During the August 13, 2020 Murray Board of Education meeting, the Murray Board of Education voted to amend the 2020-2021 Murray Independent School District (MISD) Return to School Plan, and begin Online Instruction for all MISD students, August 24, 2020.

The Murray Board of Education will continue to monitor and assess the COVID cases in the Murray and Calloway County community on a daily basis. In the event a decline is seen in COVID cases, a special called Murray Board of Education meeting will be held to evaluate beginning in-person classes prior to the Governor’s Sept. 28 in-person date recommendation.

During the August 13, 2020 Murray Board of Education meeting, the Murray Board of Education voted to amend the 2020-2021 Murray Independent School District (MISD) Return to School Plan, and begin Online Instruction for all MISD students, August 24, 2020.

The Murray Board of Education will continue to monitor and assess the COVID cases in the Murray and Calloway County community on a daily basis. In the event a decline is seen in COVID cases, a special called Murray Board of Education meeting will be held to evaluate beginning in-person classes prior to the Governor’s Sept. 28 in-person date recommendation.

MURRAY.KYSCHOOLS.US
MISD Returning to School 20-21

post_text:
Murray High Speech Takes National Stage

-Two Murray High School Speech Team members participated in the National Speech and Debate Association Tournament online in June. Seniors Chellam Antony and Isaac Gallimore earned spots to represent the Commonwealth on the national stage and competed against more than two hundred students from across the country and around the world in their individual events. Antony competed in Humorous Interpretation and Gallimore competed in U.S. Extemp.

Gallimore closes his high school competition career having achieved the rank of Distinction as a member of the National Speech and Debate Association. Antony ends her competition career with the rank of Special Distinction.

Antony and Gallimore are 2020 MHS graduates.
This marks the 27th national tournament appearance for the Tigers. The Murray High School Speech Team is coached by Michael Robinson.

post_text:
Photo Credits: - Top (left to right): Katelynn Stanczyk, Raegan Settle. Bottom: Mia Todd, Chellam Antony, and Kat Jenkins.

MURRAY HIGH SPEECH TEAM ADVANCES TO STATE FINALS

Michael Robinson, Murray High School Speech coach, announced six members of the Murray High Speech Team have advanced to the final round (top six) of the Kentucky High School Speech League (KHSSL) State Tournament.

Murray High students advanced in the following events: IMPROMPTU SPEAKING - Katelynn Stanczyk, Mia Todd; DECLAMATION - Katelynn Stanczyk; IMPROVISATIONAL DUO - Chellam Antony/Kat Jenkins; BROADCASTING - Raegan Settle; and HUMOROUS INTERP - Chellam Antony.

The state tournament is being held online for the first time ever. This is also the 100th anniversary of the KHSSL State Speech Tournament. Final rounds will be judged this weekend and awards will be announced Monday. The Murray High Speech Team is coached by Michael Robinson, Selena McPherson, Doris Cella, and Randy Patterson.

Congratulations! #murrayschools

post_text:
The Murray High School Speech Team has advanced thirteen entries into semifinal competition at the Kentucky High School Speech League Virtual State Tournament. Murray High won first in the region back in February.

Murray High Speech Team students advanced to semifinals competition (top twelve in the state) in the following events: Broadcasting - Raegan Settle; Declamation - Raegan Settle, Katelynn Stanczyk; Duo Interpretation - Korey Knight/Skylar Swalls; Extemp - Mia Todd; Humorous Interpretation - Chellam Antony; Impromptu - Mia Todd, Katelynn Stanczyk; Improv Duo - Jesse Adams/Gabriel Crass and Chellam Antony/Kat Jenkins; Poetry - Chellam Antony; Prose - Ella Brown-Terry; and Storytelling - Kat Jenkins.

Semifinal competition begins this week and finalists (top six) will be announced on May 13th. The Murray High School Speech Team is coached by Michael Robinson, Selena McPherson, Doris Cella, and Randy Patterson. #murrayschools

post_text: The Murray Independent School District (MISD) announced a celebratory 2020 Spring Sports MHS Parade, Monday, April, 27, at 6 p.m. Murray High School wishes to Celebrate MHS Spring Sports Seniors by showcasing and honoring our 2020 Spring Sports athletes, with an MHS Spring Sports parade throughout the community to honor our 2020 MHS Spring Athletes. Please join the parade route and cheer for the Tiger Seniors who, due to the COVID-19 Pandemic, lost their final year of representing our Tiger Spring Sports. MHS Alumni, former MISD employees, and current staff are invited to welcome and join our 2020 teams along the route. Our MHS seniors will be in a slow parade spanning from Murray Middle School, to Murray Elementary School, and finishing at Murrah High School Athletic Complex. The Murray Independent School District announced beginning, Monday, April 20, there will be only one free food distribution point for the remainder of the 2020 school year.

Effective Monday, April 20 through May 15, there will be only one pick-up service location offered for distribution of free food for MISD families. The pick-up will be at Murray Middle School, 801 Main Street, from 11 a.m. to 12 p.m. on Monday and Thursday of each week. Monday pick-ups will provide breakfast and lunch meals for Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. Thursday pick up will provide breakfast and lunch meals for Thursday, Friday and Saturday.

As of Friday, April 17, the MISD has served 26,626 meals to MISD families and community. #murrayschools

During NTI Instruction, Murray High School Spanish Teacher Lauren Hines and her AP Spanish students created a PSA in Spanish including the ten steps recommended by Governor Beshear to stop the spread of COVID 19. Students and faculty filmed and recorded each of the steps and Chellam Antony, MHS senior, edited the video.

“I wanted to offer my seniors a new and fun NTI assignment for the day prior to Spring Break while doing something positive for our community and reaching out to native Spanish speakers in our area. They did an excellent job and I hope that this encourages everyone to model and practice the correct behaviors in order to protect our community,” said Hines.
#murrayschools

post_text:
Congratulations to Emily Burditt, MHS sophomore, named the MHS 2020-2021 Drum Major with the MHS Tiger Marching Band.
Tim Zeiss, MHS Band director, said Burditt was named Drum Major after conducting drum major tryouts virtually. Zeiss, along with a colleague who conducts drum major clinics in West Tennessee, set up the virtual tryout through Google Meet. Hunter Carter, MES music teacher, and former MSU Racer Band Drum Major, assisted with the on-line judging panel.
Zeiss said all eight candidates appeared virtually (one at a time), with altered voice commands for each chosen piece of music. “Overall it worked well, considering the circumstances,” Zeiss said. “We altered voice commands to prevent shouting voice levels from the individual’s home."
Burditt has been a percussionist member of the MISD band since sixth grade. She is the daughter of Mary and Keith Burditt, Murray. #murrayschools

Dan Hicks, Area Technology principal, and his staff of seven instructors: Carpentry, Auto Tech, Electrical, Pre-Nursing, Culinary, Machine Tool, and Tooling, are providing Non-Traditional Instruction (NTI) to their students during the mandated COVID-19 closure by Kentucky Governor Andy Beshear.

NTI is being offered to the 337 ATC Murray and Calloway students through Google Forms, CDX online, Tooling U Online, workbooks, and an online research project for starting a restaurant.

Dan Hicks, ATC director, said the 337 ATC (freshman, sophomore, junior and senior ) students are being contacted by email. “If students do not respond, parents are contacted by email. Phone calls are also being made to students and parents. Students without access to the internet, are being sent home NTI packets.”

For full story visit:
www.murray.kyschools.us

#murrayschools

post_text:
Due to the recent confirmation of a COVID-19 case in Calloway County by the local Health Department, the Murray Independent School District will be closed to students through April 17, 2020. Non-Traditional Instruction (NTI) will continue through this period. The MISD Spring Break (April 6-10) will still be observed. During spring break, all MISD facilities will be closed. There will be no food services or Non-Traditional Instruction (NTI) provided April 6-10.

Coy Samons, MISD superintendent, continues to follow the steps as recommended by Governor Andy Beshear, Kevin Brown, Kentucky Department of Education interim commissioner, and local agencies in an effort to care for all involved. “During this difficult time, we appreciate the patience and support displayed by our Tiger families and community.”

The MISD continues to advise the community to follow the recommended social distancing practices and CDC guidelines. For more information visit: www.murray.kyschools.us #murrayschools

Shout Out to the MMS 4-5 Academic Team

The MMS 4-5 academic team competed in the Governor’s Cup Regional tournament on Saturday, Feb. 29 hosted by Trigg County Middle School.

The MMS quick recall team finished second and the team finished third overall with many individual medalists. Adeline Pitman placed first in composition and fourth in arts and humanities. post_text:
Reminder tomorrow is deadline for the MISD CENSUS 2020 Art Competition to promote CENSUS 2020 awareness. MISD Students (P-1, 2-3, 4-5, 6-8, 9-12 grades) are invited to participate in the CENSUS 2020 Competition.
Today Ladawn Hale, Partnership Specialist with the U.W. Census Bureau, spoke to Coach Turner's U.S. Government classes regarding the importance of the 2020 Census. MES and MMS students are learning the importance of being counted in the U.S. CENSUS 2020.

The 2020 responses will provide the basis for distributing more than $675 billion in federal funds to states and communities each year for the next 10 years—including money for important school programs and services such as:
Special education, Free and Reduced Price lunch, Class Size Reduction, Classroom Technology, Teacher Training, After-School Programs and Head Start. #murrayschools

Murray High School band members recently performed with the Kentucky Music Education Association (KMEA) All State Band performance at Whitney Hall in Louisville’s Kentucky Center of the Arts.

Senior- Kat Jenkins- Trumpet (3rd time in all state), Sophomore- Jeremiah Morris- Trombone (2nd time in all state), Sophomore- Carleigh Mollette- Tuba (1st time in all state), and Freshman- Hannah McKibben- Mallets (1st time in all state).

These students were among the top students in Kentucky chosen from a blind audition in December, that included 900 students, to play with their respective band.
Band Directors are Tim Zeiss and Beth Stribling.#murrayschools

post_text:
Bradley Dawson, Murray High School senior, has been named as a finalist in the annual 2020 National Merit Scholarship Program (NMSC).
The selection of some 7,500 Merit Scholarship winners from this group of more than 15000 Finalists is now in progress, In March, NMSC will begin mailing scholarship offers to winners at their home addresses and confidential notices to their high school principals.
Four major news media announcements of Merit Scholar designees will be made by NMSC in April, May, June July. Merit Scholarship awards are of three types.
Tony Jarvis, MHS Principal, congratulates Dawson. "Murray High is very excited about Bradley's next step in the National Merit process. He's a fantastic example of what our students embody from character, integrity, enthusiasm, and knowledge. He is such a deserving candidate and I hope he becomes a part of that select company."
Dawson is the son of Melanie and Roger Dawson, Murray. #murrayschools

Pictured: Heidi Mallory (guidance counselor & MMS Student Council Sponsor), Danielle Schwettman (CCMS FRYSC Coordinator) and Cody Brown (CCMS Student Council Sponsor)

Each year the Murray Middle School (MMS) and Calloway County Middle School (CCMS) Student Councils partner together to raise money for a local charity. MMS and CCMS partnered for an Eighth Grade Unite Night to benefit the Family Resource Youth Services Centers (FRYSC) of each respective school district. MMS and CCMS Student Councils spearheaded efforts to raise money through business donations, charity basketball event, and a chili supper. In all, CCMS and MMS student councils raised over $1200 to split between the MMS and CCMS FRYSC centers #murrayschools

The 2020 Census count impacts the federal funds that communities receive each year for programs and services that are critical for schools, students, and younger children, such as:

Special education, Head Start, after-school programs, and classroom technology.
Food assistance, including free and reduced-price school lunches.
Maternal and child health programs.
(Special thanks to WMHS TV 13 for producing our Census 2020 Public Service Announcement.) #murrayschools

post_text:
Murray, Ky., Jan. 10---Mechelle Morgan, Murray Independent School District Digital Learning Coach, announced Murray Middle School “STEAM in the Middle School,” program is the recipient of a a $5,000 grant from Battelle Education TSIN/STEMx STEM Classroom Grants, sponsored by TVA and BVI.
TVA and its partners have awarded $600,000 in STEM Grants for the 2019-2020 school year to 144 schools located in Alabama, Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, North Carolina and Tennessee. Murray is one of the five Kentucky (Bowling Green, Glasgow, Lewisburg, and Russellville) schools awarded. MMS competed with almost 400 applications requesting over $1.2 million in award funding.
Morgan said funds will be used to purchase IPADS, alongside other technology tools that MMS currently offers in the Innovation Hub to promote Science, Technology, Engineering, Art and Math (STEAM) education.

TVA and its partners have awarded $600,000 in STEM Grants for the 2019-2020 school year to 144 schools located in Alabama, Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, North Carolina and Tennessee. Murray is one of the five Kentucky (Bowling Green, Glasgow, Lewisburg, and Russellville) schools awarded. MMS competed with almost 400 applications requesting over $1.2 million in award funding.
Morgan said funds will be used to purchase IPADS, alongside other technology tools that MMS currently offers in the Innovation Hub to promote Science, Technology, Engineering, Art and Math (STEAM) education.

post_text:
Murray High School is proud to announce Kimberly Pidcock as our new Murray High School Softball coach. She was previously the assistant coach under Brant Shutt. Kimberly is a 2004 graduate of Calloway County High School, where she was an outfielder and played varsity for three years

Kimberly has coached at many levels for 11 years, including MYSBA, FASA, USSSA, Middle School, and High School. She is a Murray State graduate, holding a Bachelor’s Degree in Exercise Science and a Master’s Degree in Occupational Safety and Health. Currently, Kimberly is a substitute teacher for the Murray Independent School District. She is married to Craig Pidcock and has four children. #murrayschools

post_text:
(left to right) : Chuck Fuller, VFW Chairman of Patriotic Awards Programs; Kerry Vu, honorable mention; Jackson Kimbro, honorable mention; Amolika Chanda, tied for first local and regional winner; Alaina Mitchum, third place; Leanne Wortham, tied for first place local; Jessica Sager, ELA 7 teacher; and Dave Wilson, Post Commander, VFW Herman Eddie Roberts, Jr Post 6291

-Local Post 6291 Veterans of Foreign Wars announced winners of their recent “Patriot’s Pen” essay competition. There were a total of 91 contest submissions from throughout Murray, and MMS took top recognitions of the awards in this category. One entrant for each 15 essays are eligible to move forward to the District 1 (West Kentucky). Out of the six essays that were forwarded, Murray Middle School Murray had five. These competed of their own merit, with no indication of their placement in the Local context. Amolika's Chanda’s essay received first place at the District level and was forwarded to the State, where she will be graded against the winners of 13 other districts. #murrayschools

Lou Carter, Murray Independent School District (MISD)Assistant Superintendent Student Services and Director of Pupil Personnel, and Whitney York, Murray Independent School District (MISD) Assistant Superintendent Instruction, Curriculum & Human Resources, have been named to the 2020 Kentucky Women in Education Leadership (KWEL) Class. Carter and York will be inducted into the class during the third annual Women’s (Women Take The Lead) Forum in January in Louisville.

Carter and York were selected with 31 Kentucky female professional women education leaders who were nominated for the 2020 class and exemplify the mission of KWEL: (to maintain a community by promoting exemplary quality, equity and self-confidence through personal leadership growth, mentorship, and support in career advancement).

For full story visit: https://www.murray.kyschools.us/news/1671177/misd-assistant-superintendents-named-to-kwel-2020-class #murrayschools

post_text:
MMS Thanks members of the Brad Deming Memorial Bike Fund and Carl and Joy Doran, owners of Snipe Creek Lodge, for making this dream a reality today to 15 Murray Middle School Students. The group of hunting and fishing buddies continue a fund-raising drive in memory of their late friend, Brad Deming. Deming originated the idea and now has grown to 500 bikes distributed to 5 different states. Carl and Joy Doran assisted this event in donating a hunting trip to these fund-raising efforts.

Anthony Landreth and team members of the Brad Deming Memorial Bike Fund visited MMS this week and gifted 15 MMS students with new bicycles. They worked with the Murray FRYSC (Tiger Christmas) to identify students who received the bikes. (seven boys and eight girls received bikes)

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YPCNiJ0oqRM&feature=youtu.be
For more information on the Brad Deming Memorial Bike Fund visit the above link. #murrayschools

We applaud Murray Elementary School third—grader Analise Renfroe (far left), who placed second in the 3-4-grade division of the WKEC Regional Spelling Bee for Deaf and Hard-of-Hearing Students. Renfroe qualified for the state bee to be held March 3 in Elizabethtown.

Photo: MES third-grader Analise Renfroe, Muhlenberg South Elementary School fourth-grader Sophia McIntosh and Indian Hills Elementary School fourth-grader Jemma Carroll show their words during a practice round at the WKEC Regional Spelling Bee for Deaf and Hard-of-Hearing Students held Tuesday in Princeton. Renfroe placed second and Carroll placed first. Both qualified for the state bee held March 3 in Elizabethtown. (Photo credit: The Paducah Sun).

post_text:
Chellam Antony, a Murray High School senior, has been named a 2020 class of the Coca-Cola Scholars Program Semifinalist. Antony is now in the running for 150 college scholarships worth $20,000.

Moving to the next round of the selection process to become a Coca-Cola Scholar and receive a $20,000 college scholarship, Antony is among the 1,928 high school seniors selected as Semifinalists from a pool of 93,075 submitted applications from across the country based on their academic excellence, leadership and service demonstrated in school and community activities.

Antony will now complete Phase 2 applications, which include essays, recommendations, and transcripts. An independent selection committee will review the applications and select 250 Regional Finalists by the end of January to participate in online or in-person interviews. For full story visit: www.murray.kyschools.us
#murrayschools
Coca-Cola Scholars Foundation

Chellam Antony, a Murray High School senior, has been named a 2020 class of the Coca-Cola Scholars Program Semifinalist. Antony is now in the running for 150 college scholarships worth $20,000.

Moving to the next round of the selection process to become a Coca-Cola Scholar and receive a $20,000 college scholarship, Antony is among the 1,928 high school seniors selected as Semifinalists from a pool of 93,075 submitted applications from across the country based on their academic excellence, leadership and service demonstrated in school and community activities.

Antony will now complete Phase 2 applications, which include essays, recommendations, and transcripts. An independent selection committee will review the applications and select 250 Regional Finalists by the end of January to participate in online or in-person interviews. For full story visit: www.murray.kyschools.us
#murrayschools
Coca-Cola Scholars Foundation

post_text:
Congratulations to our 15 MMS seventh and eighth grade band members who were selected to the 2020 All District Honor Band. They competed with students from middle schools in a 13 county area. These recipients will perform January 11 for the All District Honor Band. (front row): Leo D’Ambrosio,(timpani, he also was selected on snare and mallets, but chose timpani), Leah Jenkins, 1st chair oboe, Marli Mehta, 1st chair French Horn, Amolika Chanda, 1st chair Euphonium/Baritone ,and Tatum Decker, horn.
Second Row: Aurora Stewart, alto sax, Hailey Hale, Battery Percussion, Sage Mize-Harper, Clarinet, Griffin Klotz ,Clarinet, and Rianna Peng, Clarinet.
Third Row: Jackson Morris, 2nd chair trumpet , Evan Bailey, tuba, Maya Swartz, mallets, Emma Pogue, 1st chair Trumpet, and Rolin Chambers, trombone.

post_text: MHS Students Alex Shultz and Garrett Putz with Judge David Buckingham, MHS alumnus and Supreme Court Justice, at KYA Delegation.
shared_text:
Kentucky YMCA Youth Association
November 20, 2019 at 2:10 PM ·

One of our favorite parts of KYA is connecting our students with the servant leaders that make up Kentucky’s systems of democracy. Special thank you to Supreme Court Justice David Buckingham for sharing his knowledge and expertise with our Murray High School KYA delegation! What a treat for our students. Thank you also to board member David Perlow for organizing a great moment for this Y-chapter!

Hello Tiger Family,

It’s a party and you’re invited!

The MMS Speech Team will be hosting a fundraiser this Saturday, November 23 from 9a.m. to noon in the MMS cafeteria. We will be having a paint party! We will be partnering with Arts Unlocked and will be painting door hangers. Hangers are $40 each. All proceeds will go to the MMS Speech Team! Below are some designs to choose from or you can message us with a different idea you would like to do. Please pre-register on the Facebook Events page for Arts Unlocked, emailing Ashlee at Arts Unlocked at ashlee8678@gmail.com, or by emailing Mrs. Sager at jessica.sager@murray.kyschools.us. Please register no later than Tuesday, November 19th so that Ashlee can begin to cut the hangers. Door hangers will be $40, all other specialty orders (smaller pieces and ornaments) can be priced by Ashlee. Payment is due on Saturday at the event via cash or check. #murrayschools



Jessica Lanier Sager
Teacher, ELA 7
Murray Middle School

post_text: MES second grade student, Lydia Yayenie, was greeted by smiles today at MES, her first day back since her Leukemia diagnosis last winter. Lydia Yayenie was greeted by classmates in Sherri Bazzell's class, as well as her best friend, Shastri Devanshi. Lydia is receiving treatments once a week and was at St. Judes until this summer. MES supports Lydia's journey and hosted a Team Lydia fundraiser with shirts generating $1,134.84 earmarked for St. Jude. Welcome back to MES, Lydia. #murrayschools

post_text: Students in world language and geography classes with Lauren Hines, MHS Spanish and Social Studies teacher, are recognizing International Education Week (IEW), November 18-22, 2019. Students in Spanish 2 are researching and presenting information in their class on the importance of world language and cultural education, as well as cultures and customs of different areas of the world. This educational initiative is an opportunity to celebrate the benefits of international education and exchange worldwide. #murrayschools

post_text:
Murray Middle School seventh and eighth grade students(42) attended Kentucky Youth Assembly in Frankfort with MMS advisors: Hope Foster, Heidi Mallory, and Tommy Shown. MMS Advisors, Sherri Muehleman and Krista Fielder worked with students during second period, prior to attending.
Longtime dedicated MMS advisor, Hope Foster, was inducted into the KYA Advisor Hall of Fame.
Jack Richey, Maya Swartz and Jansen Hays served as the three presiding officer (Po) Candidates). While there, the group represented three bill sponsoring teams with two passing, and one of the highest ranking ranking bills was achieved by MMS. Canyon Bourque received Outstanding Delegate, Reese Hampton and Madelyn Myers were named Outstanding Speakers, Conference Life Award (2019 Delegation (for being the ONE delegation at KYA that embodied the spirit of debate best).

post_text:
Coy Samons, Murray Independent School District superintendent, announced the following MISD employees have been selected to fill recent vacancies within the Murray Independent School District:
Lou Carter, employed with the MISD since 2004 has served as a Middle School principal and Instructional Supervisor, named MISD Assistant Superintendent -Student Services & Director of Pupil Personnel.
Whitney York, former teacher and technology integration specialist since 2010, named MISD Assistant Superintendent Instruction, Curriculum & Human Resources.
Teresa Speed, employed since 2002 and former MHS principal, named Safe School Coordinator and Assistant Director of Pupil Personnel.
Ann Greenfield, employed with MISD since 2002 as teacher and former coach, will serve as the MISD athletic director.
Jim Baurer, employed since 2012 in facilities and athletics, has been named Maintenance Director.#murrayschools

post_text: Murray Elementary School (K-3) assisted in a collaborative Needline Food Drive effort with Murray State University Alpha Gamma Delta Sorority and Lamba Chi Alpha Fraternity. MES contributed 1,650 cans. Mrs. Nancy Newsome’s kindergarten class received first place donating 228 cans, and Mrs. Jackie Robinson’s first grade class donated 192 cans placing second for top donations. Total box and bag donations totaled 1,800 pounds. Amberly Munsey, MES first grade teacher, said the community service project received great support. MSU Alpha Gamma Delta and Lamba Chi Alpha members collected cans from MES. #murrayschools

post_text: MHS and CCHS junior and senior Leadership Tomorrow enjoyed Arts Day with Carrie Jerrell, LT Arts Day Chair with MSU Dept. of English & Philosophy. LT students toured Johnson Theatre, participated in Theatre activities, visited a Recording Studio, Pogue Library, Graphic Design and Printmaking, Humanities programs and concluded with a performance by EQ Blu Performance. LT students also were able to pose for a photo with Dr. Bob Jackson, MSU's president. Special thanks to Brent Menchinger, Lissa Graham, Justin Patton, Jeff McLaughlin, Emily Combs, Shawn Smee, Jim Bryant, Sarah Ellis, Sarah Cox and Chris Mitchell. #murrayschools

post_text:
Murray High School School Triple Jump record holder and Track athlete standout, Keagin Brooks, signed a letter of commitment with United States Military Academy’s Track program, known as West Point, inside the MHS Media Center.
A member of the MHS 2017 State Champion Tiger Team, Brooks is also the Kentucky High School Discus Champion. A four-year member of the MHS Track team, lettering the current three years, Brooks is a two-time Amateur Athletic Union National Javelin champion. A New Balance All American in Javelin recipient, Brooks is a three-time USA Track and Field All American Javelin and Triple Jump and AAU All American.
A two-time Kentucky All-State first team recipient and a five-time Kentucky All State second team honoree, Brooks is a ten-time All Area 1 First Team and placed second place in Javelin at Texas Relays. Brooks is a four-time victory recipient in Collegiate Competitions and seven time regional Champion.

For full story visit: https://www.murray.kyschools.us/
#murrayschools
